    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mapping-agreement-cross-tool-validation/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Salmon's dual-phase inference algorithm and sample-specific bias models yield improved inter-replicate concordance (Supplementary Fig. 4) compared to both kallisto and eXpress. For example, when used for differential expression (DE) testing, the quantification estimates produced by Salmon exhibit markedly higher sensitivity at the same false discovery rate (Table 1c) \u2014 achieving a sensitivity 53% to 250% higher, at the same FDRs.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper validates Salmon's quantification accuracy against other tools (kallisto, eXpress) using metrics like inter-replicate concordance, sensitivity, and FDR. However, the card's specific focus on validating reimplementations of the SAME tool (e.g., Rust vs C++ versions of Salmon) is not addressed. The paper compares different tools, not different implementations of the same tool.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-nmeth-4197",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mapping-agreement-cross-tool-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Validate that a reimplementation or alternative tool produces equivalent quantification outputs within acceptable tolerance",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:42:25.979473+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mapping-agreement-cross-tool-validation/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Salmon also provides the ability to estimate abundance uncertainty due to random sampling and the ambiguity introduced by multimapping reads (Online methods). Unlike pseudoalignment, Salmon's lightweight mapping procedure tracks, by default, the position and orientation of all mapped fragments.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes Salmon's per-fragment tracking and handling of multimapping reads, but does not explicitly quantify per-read agreement between tool implementations. The card's specific methodology for cross-tool per-read validation is not demonstrated.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-nmeth-4197",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mapping-agreement-cross-tool-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "methods",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Per-read agreement quantification",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:42:25.979473+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mapping-agreement-cross-tool-validation/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Salmon encompasses both \"alignment\" and \"quantification\" in a single tool. When run in quasi-mapping mode, Salmon takes as input an index of the transcriptome and a set of raw sequencing reads (i.e., unaligned reads in FASTA/Q format) and performs quantification directly without generating any intermediate alignment files.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms Salmon produces quantification output but does not explicitly name the output file formats (quant.sf, unmapped_names.txt). The paper focuses on the quantification algorithm and accuracy metrics rather than output file specifications.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-nmeth-4197",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mapping-agreement-cross-tool-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "quant.sf and unmapped_names.txt files",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:42:25.979473+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/paired-end-read-quantification/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Salmon consists of three components: a lightweight-mapping model, an online phase that estimates initial expression levels and model parameters, and an offline phase that refines expression estimates... The online phase uses a variant of stochastic, collapsed variational Bayesian inference. The offline phase applies either a standard EM algorithm or a variational Bayesian EM algorithm",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes k-mer-based mapping (Sailfish approach) and EM/VBEM inference, but does NOT use 'selective alignment' terminology. The paper uses 'lightweight-mapping' and 'quasi-mapping' (k-mer allocation), not selective alignment. Selective alignment is a later development (salmon 2.0+) not covered in this 2017 paper. The paper does confirm EM/VBEM and TPM output.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-nmeth-4197",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "paired-end-read-quantification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Quantify transcript abundances from paired-end RNA-seq reads using selective alignment and statistical inference over equivalence classes. This skill combines fast k-mer-based mapping with EM/VBEM to produce per-transcript NumReads and TPM estimates.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:42:45.290542+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/paired-end-read-quantification/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Salmon constructs 'rich' equivalence classes over all the sequenced fragments... Collapsing fragments into equivalence classes is a well-established idea in the transcript quantification literature",
      "asbval:note": "Equivalence classes are explicitly described and used in the offline phase for EM/VBEM optimization.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-nmeth-4197",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "paired-end-read-quantification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "statistical inference over equivalence classes",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
